      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction involves the chemical interaction between reducing sugars and amino acids to form complex nitrogen-containing compounds that cause browning and flavor development. You generally need temperatures above 140°C (280°F) for this to happen efficiently on your wheat crust, though lower temperatures for longer periods can also trigger it. Be aware that excessive heat past 170°C (340°F) risks combusting breadcrumbs into char rather than achieving the desired golden-brown color.",
