      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, increasing the alkalinity (higher pH) of the dough significantly accelerates the Maillard reaction, which is why baking soda often darkens the crust of bagels and soda breads. At higher pH levels, the reacting amino acid groups become more stable and reactive, allowing the chemical process to occur more readily at slightly lower temperatures than in acidic environments. However, be careful with extreme alkalinity, as it can also inhibit the formation of specific flavor compounds like diacetyl and negatively affect the texture of the final bread.",
